            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Marco Reyes was born and raised in the foggy, close-knit community of Daly City, the son of Filipino immigrants who preached the gospel of stability. His mother, a registered nurse, and his father, a postal carrier, envisioned a future for him in medicine or engineering\u2014secure professions that justified their sacrifices. Marco, however, spent his youth filling sketchbooks with fantastical characters and sleek logos, a quiet rebellion that led him to enroll in the Graphic Design program at San Francisco State University.\n\nCollege was a disconnect. He felt the sterile glow of the computer screen was a poor substitute for the tactile creation he craved. To pay for tuition, he took a part-time job at a small, independent coffee shop in the Mission District, Golden Gate Roasters. There, amid the hiss of the espresso machine and the rich aroma of roasting beans, he found his true calling. The owner, a seasoned roaster named Elara, saw his potential. Marco learned that adjusting roast profiles by seconds and degrees was as nuanced as choosing a color palette. The immediate, sensory feedback of a perfectly pulled shot was more satisfying than any digital design. After two years, he made the difficult decision to drop out of SF State, disappointing his parents but committing fully to his newfound craft.\n\nNow 28, Marco is the Lead Barista and apprentice Roaster at the same shop. His day begins before sunrise with a 3.1-mile bicycle ride from his small Inner Richmond apartment, cutting through the quiet dawn of Golden Gate Park. His life is a routine of sensory details: the morning chill on his face, the precise weight of green coffee beans, the chatter of regulars he knows by name. He earns a modest income, but his life feels rich with purpose. His social circle is tight-knit, mostly consisting of other service industry professionals and artists, including his girlfriend, Maya, a ceramicist who appreciates his dedication to craft.\n\nMarco\u2019s connection to San Francisco is etched into his daily commute and his community in the Mission. He represents a different side of the city\u2014not the tech boom, but the persistent hum of its artists and craftspeople. His dream isn't a corporate ladder but a concrete floor of his own: a small-batch roastery and caf\u00e9, perhaps in the Outer Sunset, where he can share his passion, create a neighborhood hub, and finally show his parents that stability can be built not just with a degree, but with skilled, passionate hands."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe was 20, wiping down counters at Golden Gate Roasters. The owner, Elara, called him over to a cupping session. She had him slurp the coffee loudly, just like her. Suddenly, it wasn't just bitter liquid; it was notes of blueberry, of earth, of sun. The sterile world of his graphic design major faded. In that single, noisy slurp, he tasted a tangible career, a craft he could feel and smell. It was the moment the vector lines of his old life began to blur, replaced by a new purpose.\n\n2.\nHe remembers the crushing silence in his parents\u2019 Daly City kitchen, heavier than the coastal fog. He was 21. His mother\u2019s hands, usually so steady, were still on the table after he told them he was leaving SF State. His father just stared at the floor. It wasn\u2019t anger, but a deep, quiet disappointment that hurt more than shouting. In that moment, his dream wasn't just about coffee; it became a promise to himself to one day replace their disappointment with pride, to build a stability they could finally understand.\n\n3.\nLast winter, cycling through Golden Gate Park before dawn. A thick fog blanketed everything, muffling the city into a dream. The air was cold and sharp. For a moment, the only sounds were his tires on the damp pavement and the distant call of a foghorn. He felt utterly alone and completely connected to the city's sleeping soul. It wasn't the San Francisco of postcard views, but his\u2014a private peace he earned every morning. This solitude became the foundation of his resilience.\n\n4.\nThe first time he went to Maya\u2019s ceramics studio, about a year ago. Her hands were covered in wet clay, her focus absolute as she centered a mound on the wheel. He watched, mesmerized. The way she used subtle pressure, the intense concentration in her eyes\u2014it was the same focus he felt dialing in an espresso shot. In the earthy smell of the clay and the quiet hum of the wheel, he felt seen. He knew then she understood his world of patient, tactile creation completely.\n\n5.\nSix months ago, Elara left him alone with a new bag of Gesha beans\u2014their most expensive and delicate coffee. His hands trembled slightly as he loaded the roaster. He listened for the first crack, his senses on high alert, adjusting the flame by instinct, not just timers. When Elara cupped it the next day, she took a long slurp, closed her eyes, and just nodded. That simple, silent approval was more valuable than any diploma. It was the moment he stopped being an apprentice and truly became a roaster."
